 many vernacular derivatives in most of the languages of Europe. In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. Greek   Loukas  , Hungarian <b>Lukács</b> (see   Lukacs  ), German, Dutch, etc.   Lukas  , Polish <b>Łukasz</b>, Czech and Slovak <b>Lukáš</b>, Czech <b>Lukeš</b>, Slovenian and Croatian <b>Lukež</b> (see   Lukes  ). Compare   Luke  .","Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Lùcais</b> (see   McLucas  ).","History: Jacques Lucas <i>dit</i> Lépine from Port-en-Bessin-Huppain in Calvados, France, married Françoise Capel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1653."],"variants":[{"name":"Lekan","meanings":["Slovenian: from a vernacular form of the old personal name <i>Lukan</i>, derived from <i>Luka</i> (see   Lucas  ).","Polish: unexplained."]},{"name":"Lockett","meanings":["English (northern): from a pet form of   Lucas  ."]},{"name":"Luca","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Adolfo, Antonio, Carmine, Gasper, Giacomo, Mario, Rosario, Sal, Aldo, Antonino, Domenic, Domenico, Dominico, Guido.","Italian and Romanian: from the personal name <i>Luca</i>, from Latin   Lucas  . Compare   Louque  .","Italian (southern; <b>Lucà</b>): possibly from a short form of Greek <i>Loukanos</i>, denoting an inhabitant of Lucania (see   Lucas  )."]},{"name":"Lauck","meanings":["German (Hesse): from the personal name <i>Lukas</i> (see   Lucas  ), or from the female personal name <i>Liutgard</i> (see   Luckhardt  ).","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Ławk</b> and <b>Lawk</b>: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Ławŕeńc</i>, <i>Lawŕeńc</i>, from Latin <i>Laurentius</i> (see   Lawrence  )."]},{"name":"Lockey","meanings":["English: habitational name from Locka in Melling (Lancashire). The placename derives from Old English <i>loc</i> ‘lock, enclosure, fold’ + <i>haga</i> ‘hedge, enclosure’.","Scottish: from a pet form of   Lucas  . Compare   Lockie  ."]},{"name":"Lucio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Francisco, Jesus, Manuel, Pedro, Angel, Enrique, Felipe, Fernando, Guadalupe.","Spanish (also <b>Lucío</b>), Portuguese (<b>Lúcio</b>), and Italian: from local equivalents of the Latin personal name   Lucius  .","Galician: habitational name from Lucio in Pontevedra province, Galicia (Spain)."]},{"name":"Loukas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Greek Spero, Christos, Dimitrios, Gerasimos, Kostas, Loukas, Pantelis.","Greek: from the personal name <i>Loukas</i>, Greek form of   Lucas  ."]},{"name":"Luc","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Minh, Mui, Duong, Hong, Hung, Nu, Thanh, Duc, Dung, Hoa, Huu, Long, Hang, Heung, Tong.  French Pierre, Jean, Gabrielle, Germain, Sylvain.","French: from the personal name <i>Luc</i>, a vernacular form of   Lucas  .","French: topographic name derived from Latin <i>lucus</i> ‘wood’, or a habitational name from any of the places in Aveyron and Lozère named with this word."]},{"name":"Laux","meanings":["South German: from a vernacular form of the personal name   Lucas  . Compare   Loucks  ."]},{"name":"Lockie","meanings":["Scottish:","perhaps from the Scottish personal name <i>Lockie</i>, <i>Luckie</i>, a pet form of   Lucas  .","variant of   Lockey   1."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Lucas II was born in 1410, in England, United Kingdom, his father, John Lucas I, was 20 and his mother, Lady John Lucas I, was 15. He had at least 2 daughters with Lady Jane O’Sullivan. He died in 1474, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1410–1474":"1410–1474","1415–1435":"1415–1435","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1503":"1503","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1410":"1410","1474":